{
  "presentation": {
    "topics": [
      {
        "id": "title",
        "title": "Title Slide",
        "slides": [
          {
            "type": "title",
            "title": "SQLite Architecture (Elite)",
            "subtitle": "Engineering the World's Most Deployed Database <br> Internal Mechanics, VFS, and Performance Engineering"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "id": "sqlite-introduction",
        "title": "1. Introduction to SQLite",
        "slides": [
          {
            "type": "topic-title",
            "title": "1. What is SQLite?",
            "subtitle": "The Zero-Configuration, Serverless Storage Engine."
          },
          {
            "type": "content",
            "title": "Defining Features",
            "box": {
              "list": [
                {
                  "emoji": "📦",
                  "text": "<strong>Self-Contained:</strong> No external dependencies."
                },
                {
                  "emoji": "🚫",
                  "text": "<strong>Serverless:</strong> No separate server process."
                },
                {
                  "emoji": "📑",
                  "text": "<strong>Single File:</strong> The entire database is a single disk file."
                }
              ],
              "title": "A C-language library that implements a small, fast, self-contained, high-reliability, full-featured, SQL database engine."
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "content",
            "title": "Ubiquity",
            "box": {
              "list": [
                {
                  "emoji": "📱",
                  "text": "<strong>Mobile:</strong> Android, iOS, and IoT."
                },
                {
                  "emoji": "💻",
                  "text": "<strong>Desktop:</strong> Browsers (Chrome, Firefox), macOS, Windows."
                },
                {
                  "emoji": "🚗",
                  "text": "<strong>Automotive:</strong> Infotainment systems."
                }
              ],
              "title": "SQLite is found in nearly every modern electronic device."
            }
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "id": "sqlite-internals",
        "title": "2. Inside the Black Box",
        "slides": [
          {
            "type": "topic-title",
            "title": "2. Internal Architecture",
            "subtitle": "How SQLite processes a query."
          },
          {
            "type": "content",
            "title": "The Big Picture",
            "box": {
              "list": [
                {
                  "emoji": "🧩",
                  "text": "<strong>Front-End:</strong> Tokenizer, Parser, Code Generator."
                },
                {
                  "emoji": "⚙️",
                  "text": "<strong>Back-End:</strong> B-Tree, Pager, VFS (Virtual File System)."
                }
              ],
              "title": "A stack of layers from the Tokenizer to the OS interface."
            }
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "id": "vdbe",
        "title": "3. The VDBE (Virtual Database Engine)",
        "slides": [
          {
            "type": "topic-title",
            "title": "3. The VDBE",
            "subtitle": "SQLite's internal bytecode processor."
          },
          {
            "type": "content",
            "title": "Bytecode Architecture",
            "box": {
              "list": [
                {
                  "emoji": "📜",
                  "text": "<strong>Instructions:</strong> Opcode + P1, P2, P3, P4, P5 parameters."
                },
                {
                  "emoji": "💻",
                  "text": "<strong>Execution:</strong> The Virtual Machine runs this bytecode to fetch/modify data."
                }
              ],
              "code": "EXPLAIN SELECT * FROM users WHERE id = 10;",
              "title": "SQLite doesn't interpret SQL directly; it compiles it to bytecode."
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "content",
            "title": "Registers & Stack",
            "box": {
              "list": [
                {
                  "emoji": "🗄️",
                  "text": "<strong>Efficiency:</strong> Less data movement between memory locations."
                }
              ],
              "title": "The VDBE is a register-based VM (unlike JVM which is stack-based)."
            }
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "id": "pager-btree",
        "title": "4. B-Tree & Pager Layer",
        "slides": [
          {
            "type": "topic-title",
            "title": "4. Storage Engine",
            "subtitle": "How data is organized on disk."
          },
          {
            "type": "content",
            "title": "The B-Tree",
            "box": {
              "list": [
                {
                  "emoji": "🌳",
                  "text": "<strong>Table B-Trees:</strong> Key is the RowID, data in leaves."
                },
                {
                  "emoji": "🌲",
                  "text": "<strong>Index B-Trees:</strong> Key is the index value + RowID."
                }
              ],
              "title": "Organizes data into hierarchical pages for fast lookup."
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "content",
            "title": "The Pager",
            "box": {
              "list": [
                {
                  "emoji": "📟",
                  "text": "<strong>Caching:</strong> The pager keeps frequently used pages in memory."
                },
                {
                  "emoji": "🔒",
                  "text": "<strong>Locking:</strong> Coordinates access between multiple processes."
                }
              ],
              "title": "Manages reading/writing fixed-size pages (usually 4KB)."
            }
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "id": "concurrency-wal",
        "title": "5. Concurrency & WAL",
        "slides": [
          {
            "type": "topic-title",
            "title": "5. Concurrency",
            "subtitle": "How SQLite handles multi-process access."
          },
          {
            "type": "content",
            "title": "Legacy Journaling",
            "box": {
              "list": [
                {
                  "emoji": "📝",
                  "text": "<strong>DELETE/TRUNCATE:</strong> Original pages are stored in a journal file."
                },
                {
                  "emoji": "🔒",
                  "text": "<strong>Locking:</strong> Writers block all readers (Limited concurrency)."
                }
              ],
              "title": "Original Rollback Journal mechanism."
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "content",
            "title": "WAL Mode (Elite)",
            "box": {
              "list": [
                {
                  "emoji": "⚡",
                  "text": "<strong>Features:</strong> Readers don't block writers. Very fast commits."
                },
                {
                  "emoji": "📂",
                  "text": "<strong>Mechanism:</strong> Changes go to a -wal file; periodic checkpoints move them to the DB."
                }
              ],
              "code": "PRAGMA journal_mode=WAL;",
              "title": "Write-Ahead Logging transforms performance."
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "content",
            "title": "Shared-Memory Files",
            "box": {
              "list": [
                {
                  "emoji": "🧠",
                  "text": "<strong>Fast IPC:</strong> Uses mmap() for lightning-fast synchronization between processes."
                }
              ],
              "title": "The -shm file coordinates connections in WAL mode."
            }
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "id": "vfs-layer",
        "title": "6. The VFS Layer",
        "slides": [
          {
            "type": "topic-title",
            "title": "6. OS Abstraction",
            "subtitle": "The secret to SQLite's portability."
          },
          {
            "type": "content",
            "title": "Virtual File System",
            "box": {
              "list": [
                {
                  "emoji": "🌉",
                  "text": "<strong>Standard:</strong> unix-dotkf, unix-excl, win32-longpath."
                },
                {
                  "emoji": "🛡️",
                  "text": "<strong>Custom:</strong> You can write a VFS to store data in a ZIP file or across a network."
                }
              ],
              "title": "SQLite doesn't talk to the OS directly; it uses a VFS object."
            }
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "id": "manifest-typing",
        "title": "7. Manifest Typing & Flex-Type",
        "slides": [
          {
            "type": "topic-title",
            "title": "7. Type System",
            "subtitle": "SQLite's unique 'Typeless' architecture."
          },
          {
            "type": "content",
            "title": "Manifest vs Static Typing",
            "box": {
              "list": [
                {
                  "emoji": "🤯",
                  "text": "<strong>Flexibility:</strong> You can store a string in an INTEGER column."
                },
                {
                  "emoji": "🗜️",
                  "text": "<strong>Storage:</strong> SQLite automatically uses the smallest storage class for each value."
                }
              ],
              "title": "In SQLite, the datatype is a property of the value itself, not the column."
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "content",
            "title": "STRICT Tables (since 3.37.0)",
            "box": {
              "code": "CREATE TABLE users (id INT PRIMARY KEY) STRICT;",
              "title": "For developers who want traditional rigid typing."
            }
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "id": "advanced-sql",
        "title": "8. Advanced SQL Power",
        "slides": [
          {
            "type": "topic-title",
            "title": "8. Modern SQL",
            "subtitle": "Pro-level SQL features in 1MB of C code."
          },
          {
            "type": "content",
            "title": "Recursive CTEs",
            "box": {
              "code": "WITH RECURSIVE cnt(x) AS (\n  SELECT 1 UNION ALL SELECT x+1 FROM cnt\n  LIMIT 100\n) SELECT * FROM cnt;",
              "title": "Solving graph problems and generating sequences."
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "content",
            "title": "JSON functions",
            "box": {
              "code": "SELECT json_extract(data, '$.user.id') FROM logs;",
              "title": "High-performance JSON document support."
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "content",
            "title": "Generated Columns",
            "box": {
              "code": "full_name TEXT GENERATED ALWAYS AS (first || ' ' || last)",
              "title": "Computed values stored or calculated on-the-fly."
            }
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "id": "distributed-sqlite",
        "title": "9. Distributed SQLite & The Future",
        "slides": [
          {
            "type": "topic-title",
            "title": "9. The Edge",
            "subtitle": "Taking SQLite beyond a single node."
          },
          {
            "type": "content",
            "title": "LiteFS (Fly.io)",
            "box": {
              "list": [
                {
                  "emoji": "🚢",
                  "text": "<strong>Replication:</strong> Streams changes to replicas globally."
                }
              ],
              "title": "FUSE-based replication for SQLite."
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "content",
            "title": "LibSQL / Turso",
            "box": {
              "list": [
                {
                  "emoji": "☁️",
                  "text": "<strong>Serverless:</strong> HTTP interface, multi-tenancy."
                }
              ],
              "title": "The SQLite fork designed for the cloud."
            }
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "id": "optimization",
        "title": "10. Performance Tuning",
        "slides": [
          {
            "type": "topic-title",
            "title": "10. Tuning",
            "subtitle": "Squeezing every drop of performance."
          },
          {
            "type": "content",
            "title": "PRAGMA Power",
            "box": {
              "list": [
                {
                  "emoji": "💨",
                  "text": "<strong>synchronous=OFF:</strong> Extreme speed (at risk of corruption)."
                },
                {
                  "emoji": "💾",
                  "text": "<strong>cache_size:</strong> controlling the pager cache."
                },
                {
                  "emoji": "⏲️",
                  "text": "<strong>busy_timeout:</strong> Handling lock contention."
                }
              ]
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "content",
            "title": "EXPLAIN QUERY PLAN",
            "box": {
              "code": "EXPLAIN QUERY PLAN SELECT * FROM orders WHERE cid = 5;",
              "title": "Reading the VDBE optimization paths."
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "content",
            "title": "Incremental Vacuum",
            "box": {
              "code": "PRAGMA auto_vacuum = INCREMENTAL;\nPRAGMA incremental_vacuum(100); # Reclaim up to 100 pages",
              "title": "Reclaiming space without locking the whole database."
            }
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "id": "extensions",
        "title": "11. SQLite Extensions",
        "slides": [
          {
            "type": "topic-title",
            "title": "11. Extensions",
            "subtitle": "Expanding the core with modular features."
          },
          {
            "type": "content",
            "title": "FTS5 (Full-Text Search)",
            "box": {
              "code": "CREATE VIRTUAL TABLE docs USING fts5(title, body);",
              "title": "Professional-grade search engine built into SQLite."
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "content",
            "title": "R-Tree & Geospatial",
            "box": {
              "code": "CREATE VIRTUAL TABLE spatial_idx USING rtree(id, minX, maxX, minY, maxY);",
              "title": "Efficient spatial queries for maps and sensors."
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "content",
            "title": "Session Extension (Elite)",
            "box": {
              "list": [
                {
                  "emoji": "🔄",
                  "text": "<strong>Changeset:</strong> Capture all changes made to a database."
                },
                {
                  "emoji": "📡",
                  "text": "<strong>Sync:</strong> Send the changeset to another node to merge."
                }
              ],
              "title": "Extracting changesets for offline sync."
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "content",
            "title": "Loadable Extensions",
            "box": {
              "code": ".load ./uuid.so",
              "title": "Loading C-shared libraries at runtime."
            }
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "id": "compilation-amalgamation",
        "title": "12. The Amalgamation",
        "slides": [
          {
            "type": "topic-title",
            "title": "12. Build Process",
            "subtitle": "Why SQLite is just two files."
          },
          {
            "type": "content",
            "title": "The Amalgamation",
            "box": {
              "list": [
                {
                  "emoji": "📦",
                  "text": "<strong>Benefits:</strong> Easier to embed. Compiler can optimize across the whole engine (Inter-procedural optimization)."
                }
              ],
              "title": "All 100+ source files combined into one giant `sqlite3.c` file."
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "content",
            "title": "Compile-Time Options",
            "box": {
              "code": "-DSQLITE_THREADSAFE=0 # Single-threaded mode for 5% speed boost",
              "title": "Stripping features or enabling optimizations at compile time."
            }
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "id": "corruption-prevention",
        "title": "13. Data Integrity & Corruption",
        "slides": [
          {
            "type": "topic-title",
            "title": "13. Reliability",
            "subtitle": "How SQLite protects your data."
          },
          {
            "type": "content",
            "title": "Atomic Commit",
            "box": {
              "list": [
                {
                  "emoji": "⚛️",
                  "text": "<strong>Commit Record:</strong> The single bit flip that marks a transaction as final."
                }
              ],
              "title": "Ensuring transactions are all-or-nothing even during power loss."
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "content",
            "title": "Corruption Causes",
            "box": {
              "list": [
                {
                  "emoji": "📉",
                  "text": "<strong>Hardware:</strong> Disk failures or memory bit-flips."
                },
                {
                  "emoji": "🔧",
                  "text": "<strong>User Error:</strong> Opening a database file in a text editor."
                },
                {
                  "emoji": "🚫",
                  "text": "<strong>OS Bugs:</strong> Faulty file locking or sync implementations."
                }
              ],
              "title": "How databases die (and how to avoid it)."
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "content",
            "title": "Self-Testing (Thoroughness)",
            "box": {
              "list": [
                {
                  "emoji": "🧪",
                  "text": "<strong>Coverage:</strong> 100% of the code is tested by the public test suite."
                }
              ],
              "title": "The famous SQLite test suite."
            }
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "id": "maintenance",
        "title": "14. Database Maintenance",
        "slides": [
          {
            "type": "topic-title",
            "title": "14. Maintenance",
            "subtitle": "Keeping the file healthy."
          },
          {
            "type": "content",
            "title": "VACUUM",
            "box": {
              "code": "VACUUM;",
              "title": "Rebuilding the database to reclaim space and defragment."
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "content",
            "title": "ANALYZE",
            "box": {
              "code": "ANALYZE;",
              "title": "Updating statistics for the query optimizer."
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "content",
            "title": "CLI Power Tricks",
            "box": {
              "list": [
                {
                  "emoji": "📦",
                  "text": "<strong>.mode box:</strong> Beautifully formatted output tables."
                },
                {
                  "emoji": "⏱️",
                  "text": "<strong>.timer on:</strong> Measure execution time for every query."
                },
                {
                  "emoji": "📂",
                  "text": "<strong>.import:</strong> Fast CSV/TSV loading."
                }
              ],
              "title": "Pro-tips for the sqlite3 terminal."
            }
          }
        ]
